===Noun===
'''mould''' (American English spelling: '''mold''')
# A [[hollow]] form or [[matrix]] for [[shaping]] a [[fluid]] or [[plastic]] [[substance]]. 
# A [[frame]] or [[model]] around or on which something is [[form]ed or [[shape]]d. 
# Something that is made in or shaped on a mould. 
# The shape or pattern of a mould. 
# General shape or form; as, ''the oval mould of her face''
# [[distinctive|Distinctive]] [[character]] or type; as, ''a leader in the mould of her predecessors''
# A [[fixed]] or [[restrictive]] [[pattern]] or [[form]]
#:''His method of scientific investigation broke the '''mould''' and led to a new discovery. ''
# (''Architecture'') See [[moulding]].

====Etymology====
Via Middle English and Old French from Latin ''[[modulus]]''
====Translations====
*French: [[moulage]] (1)
===Noun===
'''mould''' (American English spelling: '''mold''')

# natural substance in the form of a woolly or furry growth of tiny fungi that appears when organic material lies for a long time exposed to (usually warm and moist) air

====Etymology====
Via Middle English from Old Norse ''[[mygla]]]''
